{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἐπιδέξῐ-ος</b>, ον, <br /> <b>towards the right</b>, i.e. <b>from left to right</b>: <br /><Level2><b>__I</b></Level2>. used by [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus only in _neuter_ _plural_ \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] as <i>adverb</i>, ὄρνυσθ᾽ ἑξείης ἐπιδέξια rise in order, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 21.141, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Smp.” 214b; περίιθι τὸν βωμὸν ἐ. 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 957; πίνειν τὴν ἐ. (i.e. κύλικα) 5th c.BC: Eupolis Comicus 325, compare 4th c.BC: Anaxandrides Comicus 1.4, 5th c.BC: Critias Philosophus, Tragicus, Elegiacus 33 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator; without idea of motion, ἕστηκεν ἐ. 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator “fragment” 94; sometimes as two words, ἐπὶ δεξιά, opposed to ἐπ᾽ ἀριστερά, 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 7.238, cf. Eust.ad 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” [same place]; ἐπὶ δ. χειρός 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 6.19, 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 25.18; τὰ ἐπὶ δ., opposed to τὰ ἐπ᾽ ἀριστερά, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.93, 4.191, 6.33. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__I.2</b></Level3>. <b>auspicious, lucky</b>, ἀστράπτων ἐ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.353. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2>. later as <i>adjective</i>, ={δεξιός}, <b>on the right hand</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “An.” 6.4.1, etc.; τἀπιδέξια\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>the right side</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Av.” 1493 (Lyric poetry); οἱ ἐ. ἄνεμοι 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Problemata” 941b12 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]. <br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3>. <b>clever, dexterous, tactful</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 1.178, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “EN” 1128a17, 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Char.” 29.4; λαβὴ φιλοσόφων ἐπιδέξιος ἡ διὰ τῶν ὤτων 4th-3rd c.BC: Zeno Citieus Stoicus 1.64 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: with <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rh.” 1381a34; ἐ. πρὸς τὰς ὁμιλίας 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 5.39.6; περί τι Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus [{1-2nd c.AD}] “Aemilius Paulus” 37, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Dio Cassius Historicus 69.10: _superlative_, Ἀφροδίτην -ωτάτην θεῶν Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus [{1-2nd c.AD}] 2.739e \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: <i>neuter</i> <i>plural</i> as <i>adverb</i>, ἐπιδέξια <b>dexterously</b>, <b>cleverly</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Anaxandrides Comicus 53.5, 3rd c.BC: Nicomachus Comicus 1.27 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; <b>elegantly</b>, ἀναβάλλεσθαι ἐ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Tht.” 175e \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: Regul. <i>adverb</i> <b>-ίως</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"3rd c.BC: Erasistratus Medicus cited in 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 7.539, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 3.19.13, 4.35.7, 1st c.AD: Cornutus Philosophus “ND” 14, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.439e. \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3>. <b>lucky, prosperous</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" τύχη 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 8.4 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>].","strongNumber":"G7401","accentedUnicode":"ἐπιδέξιος","shortDef":"fitting","mediumDef":"fitting","stepGloss":"fitting","stepTransliteration":"epidexios","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}